<!-- SECTION 3 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The forward scenarios</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">What continuation costs, by commodity, for specific importers.</h2>

<p class="prose">The Narrows model translates disruption severity into bilateral cost for specific counterparties across time horizons and toll scenarios. Japan is the primary example because it carries the highest absolute Hormuz exposure of any single importer across both LNG and crude petroleum. The figures are calculated separately by commodity, because the cost structures are not comparable.</p>

<p class="prose">For crude, rerouting costs are recalculated at current market rates: VLSFO at $1,076 per tonne and charter rates consistent with BDTI 2,795. These are approximately 1.9x and 2.5x their 2024 baselines. <strong>For LNG, there are no rerouting costs to calculate. The VaR figures represent supply that cannot move, not supply that moves at a premium.</strong></p>

